<HEADLINE> Turkey, Libya Try to Improve Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- In a sign that Turkey and Libya
are trying to improve bilateral relations, Turkish Foreign Ministry
on Friday evaluated as "successful" a Turkish parliamentary
delegation's recent visit to the Arab country.
</P>
<P>
The delegation from Turkey-Libya Parliamentary Friendship Group
concluded its five-day visit to Libya on Friday. During the visit,
Libyan President Muammar Gaddafi sent a goodwill and friendship
message to Turkish President Ahmet Necdet Sezer.
</P>
<P>
Libya's Secretary for External Relations and International
Cooperation Abdel Rahman Shalgham also invited Turkish Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit and Foreign Minister Ismail Cem to visit
Libya.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said these are important steps taken to
overcome problems between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Turkey and Libya soured four years ago when
former pro-Islamic Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan visited
the country in October 1996 and made fundamentalist remarks.
</P>
<P>
As a result of exchange of harsh statements from both sides,
Turkey called back its ambassador to Tripoli in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 when Erbakan's government was toppled under the pressure
from the powerful Turkish military who accused him of pursuing
anti-secular domestic and foreign policies, Turkey re-sent an
ambassador to Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with the Turkish delegation, Shalgham said
Turkey can prevent the emergence of fundamentalist movements both
in Libya's region and in Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
Libya also asked Turkey, its "only ally friend" in the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), to assist in determining the
location of mine fields left over from the World War II and
eliminating them, saying records of the mine fields must exist in
NATO archives.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish authorities accepted the Libyan request for
assistance and promised to do what they can with regard to NATO.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish delegation visited Turkish construction companies
working in Libya, especially on the Sub-Saharan water pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Turkey attaches importance to Libya, the road to trade with
Africa. The two countries are trying to tap into the African market
together on the basis of mutual interests.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.N. embargo on Libya was lifted in April 1999, the
country has been struggling to regain its place in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
