<HEADLINE> Iraq Claims Its Air Defenses Shot Down Another U.S. Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 19 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi military spokesman said
on Saturday that an American plane has been shut down in southern
Iraq by its anti-air defenses, the official Iraqi News Agency (INA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Yassin Jasim, major general of the Iraqi
Air Defense Command, said that the plane was shut down on July 26
and crashed in the Saudi desert.
</P>
<P>
This had resulted in the suspension of the United States and
British air raids against Iraq "for many days," he was quoted by
the INA as saying.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman did not explain why Iraq made the announcement
till almost one month later.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman claimed that Iraqi anti-aircraft artillery has
shot down more than 10 U.S. and British planes. "We have evidence
to prove that," he said, without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been challenging the U.S. and British jets patrolling
and enforcing the no-fly zones ever since the air war in December
1998 in southern and northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad does not recognize the zones, which are not directly
covered by a U.N. resolution and have been the site of almost daily
skirmishes since December 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
