<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Six Israeli companies will undertake six irrigation
projects in Turkey at a cost of 7 million U.S. dollars within the
scope of the Southeastern Anatolia Project (GAP), reported Anatolia
News Agency on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Turkey earlier requested Israel to propose firms after 30
companies had applied for the GAP irrigation projects.
</P>
<P>
Those companies are expected to start implementing the
irrigation projects at the end of 2000 after a formal agreement is
signed between Turkey's State Water Works and the Israeli
government.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt is expected to generate 1.613 billion Egyptian
pounds (460.86 million U.S. dollars) from textile products in the
first half of this year, up by 25.9 percent from 1.281 billion
pounds (366 million dollars) during the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
During the first six months of this year, textile exports
reached 52,000 tons to the value of 1.346 billion pounds (384.57
million dollars), while the figures stood at 43,000 tons worth 1.13
billion pounds (322.86 million dollars) in the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
The rise in exports was attributed to an increase in
international textile prices, cessation of anti-dumping legal
actions taken by the European Union (EU) producers and producers'
efforts to open new markets.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Used by some 10 million people worldwide, Palm pocket
computers have sold 5,000 units since they were launched on Turkish
market in January 2000.
</P>
<P>
Robotics, which is the Turkish distributor of Palm computers,
targets a sales volume of 40,000 by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Palm, a computer of U.S. origin, displays all the functions of a
home or office computer.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- The number of Jordanian banks in the Palestinian self-
rule areas has reached 12 with 55 branches by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The accounts of those banks rose to 1.95 billion Jordanian
dinars(2.79 billion U.S. dollars) by the end of 1999, up 15.1
percent from 1998, according to a report by the Central Bank of
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian bank branches in the West Bank were closed down
following Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip in
1967. Jordan reopened its banks in the Palestinian self-rule areas
after it signed a peace agreement with Israel in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
