<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Prices to Rise in Cyprus: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- An official at the Cyprus
Commerce Ministry has predicted that petrol prices in Cyprus could
rise in September under a new automatic price adjustment mechanism,
local media reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism, approved by the parliament on July 6, created a
formula that factors in several variables and spits out a result,
said Ministry official Maria Passades.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism takes into account the fluctuations in any given
month of oil price and the exchange rate between Cyprus pound and
U.S. dollar to determine whether an automatic price rise or cut is
necessary.
</P>
<P>
The parliament set the Brent Crude price of 16.97 pounds (26.81
U.S. dollars) per barrel as the baseline price against which
fluctuations would be measured. Pump prices will then rise one cent
per liter for every 1.75 pounds (2.77 dollars) that crude rises on
a monthly average over the baseline price.
</P>
<P>
With the Cyprus pound now valued at 1.58 dollars, and the
average price rise of crude oil currently 1.60 pounds (2.53
dollars) above the July baseline price, Passades said, she was "not
optimistic" that pump prices would not rise in September.
</P>
<P>
The new automatic price mechanism emerged as a solution to the
constant dispute over petrol prices between the government and the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
With the parliament's rejection to raise petrol prices, the
government paid out some 14 million pounds (22.4 million dollars)
in the first half of this year to subsidize the import of
increasingly expensive crude. 
</P>
</TEXT>
