<HEADLINE> Russian Plane in Iraq on Humanitarian Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A Russian plane arrived at the
newly opened Saddam International Airport in the capital Baghdad on
Saturday on a "humanitarian mission" to sanctions-stricken Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft, carrying humanitarian supplies, mainly baby food,
medicine and medical equipment, landed at the airport at 18:10
local time (1410 GMT).
</P>
<P>
This was the first direct flight from Moscow since the end of
the Gulf War in 1991. Russian Deputy Minister of Civil Defense and
Emergency Situations Ruslan Tsalikov, at the head of a 25-member
delegation, told reporters that his country did not ask for
permission for the flight from the United Nations Sanctions
Committee for the trip.
</P>
<P>
"we just notified it," he added. The U.N. sanctions imposed
since 1990 bar any flight to and from Iraq, but Baghdad argues
there were no Security Council resolutions forbid Iraq from flying
civilian aircraft into and out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Russia is an independent country with independent foreign
policy, Tsalikov said, expressing the hope that the visit will help
enhance bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Tsalikov will meet Iraqi officials to discuss
emergency treatments as well as safety measures in defusing
unexploded bombs.
</P>
<P>
The 1991 Gulf War, triggered by Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait,
and the constant bombardments in the two no-fly zones in southern
and northern Iraq, are believed to have left a large amount of
unexploded bombs in Iraq, threatening the lives of Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq reopened the international airport on Thursday after it was
closed for 10 years, to welcome planes from "friendly countries."
</P>
<P>
Russia, one of the five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council, has been a traditional ally and the biggest trading
partner of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz visited Moscow in July to
rally Russian support for Baghdad's efforts to have the decade-old
U.N. sanctions lifted.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been calling for an early removal of the sanctions
and has repeatedly urged the U.S. and Britain to stop patrolling
and bombing the two so-called no-fly zones in northern and southern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad does not recognize the air-exclusion zones, citing they
were imposed by the U.S. and Britain without proper U.N.
authorization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
