<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2nd Lead: Abu Sayyaf's Safety Worry Defers Release of Hostages EDS: Updates With More Details and Background </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators Saturday failed to
secure the release of all the remaining hostages held by the Abu
Sayyaf in the southern island of Jolo as widely expected because
the group alleged the military are planning to attack it.
</P>
<P>
Chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado told reporters at
the airport in the southern city of Zamboanga Saturday afternoon
that the Abu Sayyaf handed negotiators a letter in which it said
it can't free the hostages in one batch because there are military
movements in its areas, the local ABS-CBN TV station reported.
</P>
<P>
"As I know, the military has been keeping a distance. They are
not doing anything," said Aventajado, who returned from Jolo, some
150 kilometers southwest of Zamboanga, where Abu Sayyaf rebels
were expected to hand over their captives to government
negotiators.
</P>
<P>
He said the Abu Sayyaf offered in the letter to release two
European hostages which is against a directive by President Joseph
Estrada to have the hostages "all or non."
</P>
<P>
The chief negotiator said they will hold a meeting Saturday
night to assess the situation and come up with a recommendation
for the president.
</P>
<P>
The rebels are still holding the remaining 13 hostages -- three
Malaysians, two Germans, two Finns, two French, two South Africans,
one Lebanese and one Filipino they abducted from Malaysia's resort
island of Sipadan on April 23.
</P>
<P>
They also have in their hands three French TV journalist and 12
Filipino Christian evangelists who went to Jolo last month to
cover the hostage crisis and pray for the hostages.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the three Malaysians have been released,
Aventajado said he has no idea about it. He explained that Lee
Peng Wee, another government negotiator, is working for their
release while he is concentrating on the freedom of the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
They divided at the airport in Jolo and Lee's team went to
another place, he added.
</P>
<P>
Lee reportedly said Friday that the Abu Sayyaf handed over the
last three Malaysian hostages to his special emissary in the day.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Rajab Azzarouq, a former Libyan ambassador to the
Philippines who is negotiating with the kidnappers, said "we will
have to renegotiate" as the Abu Sayyaf refused to release the
hostages in on batch.
</P>
<P>
Azzarouq went to Abu Sayyaf's staging areas in Jolo to receive
the hostages expected to be freed, but the rebels handed him the
above-mentioned letter.
</P>
<P>
Expectations ran high earlier in the day that the Abu Sayyaf
would free all the remaining hostages it held in Jolo, and
ambassadors of related countries gathered at the airport of
Zamboanga to meet them.
</P>
<P>
It was said that the foreign hostages will be flown by a
chartered Libyan plane to the Libyan capital of Tripoli, where
their family members are waiting for them.
</P>
<P>
It has been widely reportedly that Libya is willing to offer 25
million U.S. dollars in ransom for the release of the hostages,
but both Tripoli and Manila have denied such reports.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Abu Sayyaf has released in batches six Malaysians,
one ailing German woman and one Filipino of the Sipadan group, and
one German journalist and two local TV reports.
</P>
<P>
The group has amassed about 5.5 million U.S. dollars in ransoms
paid for the release of the six Malaysians and the German woman,
Gen. Angelo Reyes, chief of staff of the Philippine Armed Forces,
disclosed earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
