<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visiting Japanese PM Hopes to Cooperate with Dhaka in  International Arena </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Japanese Prime Minister
Yoshiro Mori Saturday expressed the hope to further cooperate with
Bangladesh in addressing various international issues, especially
since Bangladesh is currently a non-permanent member of the U.N.
Security Council and the next NAM (Nonalignment Movement) chair
country.
</P>
<P>
Briefing newsmen here after a formal talk between Mori and
Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, a spokesman of the
Japanese Foreign Ministry said that during the talk, both prime
ministers were of the same opinion that, since the independence of
Bangladesh, "the bilateral relationship between the two countries
has been excellent." Both sides agreed upon further expansion of
the bilateral relationship, including in the economic and cultural
fields, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, Mori mentioned in the talk that
Japan has extended positive economic cooperation to Bangladesh and
that Japan will continue its cooperation for poverty alleviation
through the development of the Bangladesh economy.
</P>
<P>
Hasina expressed Bangladesh's deep appreciation for Japan being
its largest development partner.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question on the efforts made by the Japanese
government for becoming a permanent member of the U.N. Security
Council, the Japanese spokesman said that during talk with his
counterpart, Mori stressed the need of progressing forward the
discussions concerning U.N. reform, including the Security Council
reform.
</P>
<P>
Mori held the view that the reform of the Security Council
should include the expansion of both permanent and non-permanent
members of the Security Council, and the new permanent members
should include both industrialized and developing countries, the
spokesman said, adding that Hasina expressed her appreciation
concerning Japanese stance, and two prime ministers agreed to
further strengthen the two countries' cooperation within the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the plan for "people to people exchanges" mentioned
by Mori, the spokesman said that Japan will take 5000 youth from
all South Asian countries, including Bangladesh, per year as
scholars and artists for strengthening the "people to people
contacts".
</P>
<P>
Mori arrived here Saturday afternoon for a two-day official
visit on the first leg of his South Asian trip. The Japanese prime
minister will also visit Pakistan, India and Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements signed on Friday between Japan and
Bangladesh, Japan will provide Bangladesh with 16.011 billion yen
(about 147 million U.S. dollars) as loan assistance for four
development projects and 4.52 billion yen (about 39 million
dollars) as grants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
