<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Tries Again to Rescue Sunken Sub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A rescue vehicle was once again
lowered Saturday afternoon to approach the sunken Russian nuclear
submarine Kursk lying on the Barents Sea floor after failed
efforts over a week.
</P>
<P>
The submarine, with a crew of 118, has been stranded more than
100 meters deep in the sea since last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Rescue vehicles succeeded in latching onto Kursk's escape
hatch twice, but were unable to create a watertight seal and pump
out the seawater, Russian media reported.
</P>
<P>
Deformation of the hatch, likely caused when the vessel hit
the seabed, is blamed for the failures.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Vladimir Putin met senior aides in the
Kremlin to discuss the rescue operation. Prime Minister Mikhail
Kasyanov, Security Council Secretary Sergei Ivanov and Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian ship "Normand Pioneer" carrying the British mini-
submarine "LR5" is expected to arrive on the scene at about 9 p.m.
Moscow time (1700 GMT) in an attempt to dock with the "Kursk."
</P>
<P>
The state ad hoc commission on the accident saw an internal
explosion as the most likely cause for the tragedy, Murmansk
region Governor Mikhail Yevdokimov told reporters Saturday
following a meeting of the commission, which is headed by Deputy
Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov.
</P>
<P>
"This is indicated by cracks on the submarine's hull, which
cannot be explained by anything else," the Interfax news agency
quoted Yevdokimov as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the explosion occurred after the sub had already
crashed into the seabed. This "in fact eliminated the first cause
that had forced the submarine to sink to the sea bottom," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the chances to bring the submarine crew back
alive to the surface are becoming fewer and fewer.
</P>
<P>
The governor seems not to expect much of the foreign
assistance in improving the situation, saying the AS-34, AS-36 and
AS-15 vehicles employed by the Northern Fleet in the rescue
operations are not inferior to the British LR5 in their technical
performance.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "We are pinning our greatest hopes on the
Norwegians, who are bringing deep-sea divers. We hope they will
either help dock the Northern Fleet's rescue sub or latch the mini-
submarine they are bringing themselves" onto the Kursk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
