<HEADLINE> Kenya Volleyball Association Head Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Volleyball Association (
KVA) chairman Waithaka Kioni has resigned over the handling of the
scheduled national women's volleyball team's trip to Japan for two
weeks' training there.
</P>
<P>
In his resignation made public here Saturday, Kioni said he was
not impressed with the way the National Olympic Committee of Kenya
(NOCK) handled the trip of the national women's volleyball team to
Japan scheduled starting on August 20.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya women's team, that will make their Olympic debut next
month, failed to travel to Japan after NOCK could not raise 300,
000 shillings (about 4,000 U.S. dollars) intended for the team's
logistics in Japan where they would play several warm-up matches
before joining the Kenyan Games' camp in Adelaide, Australia.
</P>
<P>
The tour was organized by Kenya's Japanese coach Sadatoshi
Sugawara who also offered to pay 300,000 shillings for the team's
upkeep in Japan.
</P>
<P>
"The failure by NOCK to pay the amount and subsequent
cancellation of the tour will really affect KVA's relations with
our Japanese friends," Kioni said.
</P>
<P>
Following the failure of the Japanese trip, the 12-member
Kenyan women's volleyball team left here for Adelaide on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kioni had worked with KVA for 15 years and served as KVA
chairman for two years. 
</P>
