<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tomb Value to Be Known After Coffin Opening: Archeologist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- It is quite possible that
precious burial objects may still be inside the Laoshan Tomb
though it was looted before, an archeologist said today.
</P>
<P>
The tomb, dating back some 2,000 years ago in the Western Han
Dynasty (206 B.C.- 24 A.D.), was accidentally found early this
year in the Laoshan area, western Beijing. Archeological
excavation has gone on since then.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, archeologists discovered two small holes on
the doors of the tomb chamber and the outer cloister, which are
considered to be used by grave robbers long ago.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu Pingfang, an archeologist with the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences, the tomb robbers might only took
jewelry away, while lacquerware, bronzeware, silk and other burial
objects of greater research value would be left in the tomb.
</P>
<P>
In Chinese history, the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- 220 A.D.) and
Tang Dynasty (618-907) were the two periods when grand funeral
ceremonies were popular. The burial objects in the tombs of
aristocrats were abundant both in quantity and in variety,
according to Xu, who has taken part in many important
archeological excavations.
</P>
<P>
Some of the unearthed objects from the Laoshan Tomb indicate
that the tomb occupant would be a king of the Yan Principality
from Western Han. As a result, the funeral objects must be
surprisingly valuable.
</P>
<P>
Historic records indicate that emperors of the Han Dynasty used
one-third of the annual revenue to build imperial mausoleums, and
the tombs of the royal family were also luxurious.
</P>
<P>
"It is still too early to make a conclusion on the
archeological value of the Laoshan Tomb," said Xu. "All judgments
should be made after the coffin is opened."
</P>
<P>
On Sunday morning, China Central Television, the largest TV
station in the country, will broadcast live the excavation process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Media Reports Arousing Mass Interest in Archeology (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Li Yin, a Beijing resident, said
she has been wanting to watch the live TV program on the
excavation of the Laoshan Tomb for quite a long time.
</P>
<P>
The tomb Li Yin is talking about is the 2,000-year tomb
discovered early this year in western Beijing. Excavation of the
tomb has been going on for about eight months.
</P>
<P>
It is the second Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- 24 A.D.) tomb
discovered in the Chinese capital. The first one is the Dabaotai
tomb excavated in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Reports from newspapers, Internet and TV programs over the past
months have made the tomb a hot topic among people in China.
</P>
<P>
Since no one is allowed to visit the excavation site, people
are following media reports to get the latest information. They
also talked to other archaeologists or bought books on archeology.
</P>
<P>
A salesman from the local Xinhua Book Store said that this is
the first time that archeological books have sold so well.
</P>
<P>
The China Central Television (CCTV), the largest TV station of
the country, will broadcast live the excavation of the Laoshan
Tomb starting Sunday morning. This has aroused the interest of
more people, including Li Yin, who serves in the local government.
</P>
<P>
Li has formed a habit of discussing archeology and the
discovery of tombs with her colleagues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Media Reports Arousing Mass Interest in Archeology (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"No archeological excavation process has been shown to the
public before," said Xu Pingfang, a renowned archeologist with the
Chinese Academy of Sciences, "and descriptions in novels and some
TV series exaggerate too much about our work."
</P>
<P>
"It is the first time that we make a live broadcast on tomb
excavation and we want to let people understand what is the real
work of archeology," said Luo Hancheng, an executive producer at
CCTV.
</P>
<P>
Many unearthed funeral objects reveal that the tomb's occupant
was a king during the Western Han Dynasty, but since the coffin
has not been opened, the mystery of what is inside still has
people's attention.
</P>
<P>
"What ordinary people are concerned most about maybe is the
jewelry in the tomb, while silk, pottery, lacquerware and other
tender and fragile objects are of more value to archeological
research," Xu said.
</P>
<P>
"It is really a rare chance for the audience to see the first
appearance of 2,000-year-old objects," said Luo.
</P>
<P>
This is good news to Li Yin. She use to visit the Ming tombs,
which date back 300-600 years ago, but some replications of
cultural relics disappointed her very much.
</P>
<P>
"The reports from the media will contribute to the spread of
archeological information to the masses as well as improve their
consciousness to protect our cultural heritage," said Xu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
