<HEADLINE> 1st Lead: Abu Sayyaf's Safety Worry Defers Release of Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Abu Sayyaf rebels didn't free
its hostages in the southern island of Jolo Saturday as widely
expected, alleging there are military movements in their areas
which endanger their safety, government negotiators said.
</P>
<P>
Chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado told reporters at
the airport in the southern city of Zamboanga Saturday afternoon
that the Abu Sayyaf handed negotiators a letter in which it said
it can't free the hostages in one batch as there are military
movements in its areas, the local ABS-CBN TV station reported.
</P>
<P>
They worry about their safety, but there are no military
movements in the areas, said Aventajado, who just returned from
Jolo, some 150 kilometers southwest of Zamboanga, where Abu Sayyaf
rebels were expected to hand over their captives to government
negotiators.
</P>
<P>
The rebels are still holding the remaining 13 hostages -- three
Malaysians, two Germans, two Finns, two French, two South Africans,
one Lebanese and one Filipino they abducted from Malaysia's resort
island of Sipadan on April 23.
</P>
<P>
They also have in their hands three French TV journalist and 12
Filipino Christian evangelists who went to Jolo last month to
cover the hostage crisis and pray for the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Rajab Azzarouq, a former Libyan ambassador to the
Philippines who is negotiating with the kidnappers, said "we will
have to renegotiate" as the Abu Sayyaf wants to release the
hostages in batches, which is against a directive by President
Joseph Estrada to have them "all or non."
</P>
<P>
Azzarouq went to Abu Sayyaf's staging areas in Jolo to receive
the hostages expected to be freed, but the rebels handed him the
above-mentioned letter.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado told reporters that the rebels had offered to
release two European hostages, but Azzarouq proceeded in line with
President Estrada's directive.
</P>
<P>
Expectations ran high earlier in the day that the Abu Sayyaf
would free all the remaining hostages it held in Jolo, Sulu
province.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Abu Sayyaf has released six Malaysians, one ailing
German woman and one Filipino of the Sipadan group, and one German
journalist and two local TV reports  
</P>
</TEXT>
