<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Major Tombs of Han Dynasties Unearthed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua)-- The excavation of the Laoshan
Tomb of the Western Han Dynasty in western Beijing has aroused
great interest from the people.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949,
thousands of tombs from the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- 220 A.D.) have
been excavated.
</P>
<P>
Mawangdui Tomb: Western Han (206 B.C.- 24 A.D.) tombs excavated
in 1972 at Mawangdui, Changsha, Hunan Province. More than 3,000
burial objects of silk writings, bamboo slips, lacquerware,
pottery, Chinese herbal medicine, as well as a well-preserved
woman's corpse were found.
</P>
<P>
Tombs of the Changsha Prince and his family: Western Han tombs
at Changsha, Hunan. Over 2,000 burial relics were discovered.
Three lacquerware "Zhu," a traditional Chinese musical instrument,
were for the first time unearthed.
</P>
<P>
Mancheng Han tombs: Tombs of Liu Sheng, Prince Jing of
Zhongshan of Western Han and his wife Dou Wan, excavated in 1968
at Mancheng, Hebei Province. Two suits of "jade clothes sewn with
gold thread" along with some 10,000 burial objects were unearthed.
</P>
<P>
Dabaotai Tomb: Western Han tombs discovered in 1974 at Dabaotai,
Beijing. "Huangchang Ticou," a special wooden structure to protect
the coffin, used only by family members of the king, along with a
gorgeous full-scale carriage was unearthed for the first time in
China.
</P>
<P>
Tianchang Tombs: Western Han tombs excavated in 1992 at
Tianchang, Anhui Province. Rich well-preserved lacquerware and 28
woodworking tools which were considered to be of high importance
in archeological research.
</P>
<P>
Leitai Tombs: Large scale brick tombs from the late Eastern Han
Dynasty (25 A.D.- 220 A.D.) discovered in 1969 at Leitai, Gansu
Province. A bronze galloping horse was excavated from the tomb,
with the shape of a swallow on the right hind hoof has become the
symbol of China's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Archeological excavations in the past show that the Western Han
Dynasty mainly encased coffins into deep earth pits or caves on
high mountains, while the Eastern Han Dynasty used the brick and
stone-chambered tombs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Well-Preserved Corpse Unlikely in Beijing Ancient Tomb: Archaeologist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese archaeologist
estimated that it is unlike that a well-preserved corpse would be
found in a 2,000-year tomb currently excavated in western Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Xu Pingfang, an archaeologist with Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, explained that it was because the tomb was probably not
sealed off since part of it was found collapsed.
</P>
<P>
The tomb, located in Laoshan area about 10 kilometers west of
downtown Beijing, was discovered early this year. It is believed
to be the tomb of a king or queen of the Yan principality from the
Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- 24 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
The original corpse could be found rotten and only some bones
could be left in the coffin, Xu said. A team of archaeological
workers have been working on the tomb during the past eight months.
The occupant of the tomb is still unknown since the casket has not
been opened yet.
</P>
<P>
Ancient corpses unearthed in China are of two kinds: mummies
and soft bodies. Mummies were often found in drought-prone western
areas such as Xinjiang where the corpses can naturally turn into
mummies in the dry weather.
</P>
<P>
These mummies are different from the ones found in the pyramids
of Egypt, which were wrapped tight with cloth after the interior
organs were removed and special spices were applied from inside to
the surface of the body.
</P>
<P>
Soft bodies discovered in China were usually found in well
sealed tombs built with bricks or stones, sometimes with spices,
during the Song Dynasty (960-1279) and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
In the 1970s, a rare but well-preserved female corpse with its
skin still elastic was uncovered in a tomb dating back some 2,100
years to the Western Han Dynasty in Hunan Province, central China.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that it was because the female corpse was preserved in
a coffin sealed up without oxygen and germs. Besides, the moist
weather in the south prevented the corpse from becoming dry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Who Is Occupant of Beijing Ancient Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have been
excavating an ancient tomb dating back some 2,000 years in western
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The mystery of who is the occupant of the ancient tomb,
discovered in Laoshan area of Beijing, has aroused great public
interest and a live telecast has been planned at the site.
</P>
<P>
A wooden structure used to protect the tomb's chamber, which
has been unearthed in the ancient tomb, convinced archaeologists
that it was for a king or queen of a principality. The structure
of a tomb like the one discovered was only used for mausoleums of
emperors, queens, princes and kings of principalities during
Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- 24 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
Beijing was part of the northeastern frontier known as Yan
Principality some 2,000 years ago. Emperors of the Western Han
Dynasty had appointed 12 kings of Yan Principality within some 200
years.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists believe that the occupant of Laoshan
ancient tomb should be one of the 11 kings, since one of the 12
kings' tombs was discovered in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
They gave a list of four kings' names which are: who are King
Liu Ze, King Liu Shun, King Liu Huang and King Liu Qijia after the
possibility of other kings being buried at that tomb were excluded
in accordance with historical records and some relics unearthed
recently from the Laoshan ancient tomb.
</P>
<P>
It would be not an easy decision since no epigraphs were placed
in tombs during the Han dynasties. Archaeologists would have to
identify who the occupant was according to signets, clay seal
impressions, bamboo and wood strips with inscriptions, or marks on
bronze or lacquerware that might be found in the casket. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science, Technology Help Archaeologists Protect Relics (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Unlike archaeologists who work
with spades and brushes, Chen Yunshi guided his colleagues to
where he keeps his medicinal liquid that is used on timber just
unearthed from a nearby ancient tomb.
</P>
<P>
His team also sprays the same liquid on the wooden fence around
the tomb from time to time.
</P>
<P>
Chen, an expert on timber protection with the Chinese Academy
of Forestry Sciences, is trying to prevent timber, which is over 2,
000 years old, from becoming rotten or fragile.
</P>
<P>
Chen's team works at the site of a tomb dating back some 2,000
years ago to Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.- 24 A.D.) in Laoshan
area, about 10 kilometers west of downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The mysterious underground palace was discovered early this
year. It was mainly built with wood. Archaeologists have unearthed
a wooden structure encasing the tomb. The structure, which was
designed to prevent outside moisture and earth from entering the
tomb, was reserved only for tombs of royal family members.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the about 100 cubic meters of timber was
used to build the wooden structure discovered in the ancient tomb.
</P>
<P>
All the timber has rotten to varying degrees. Some would break
at the slightest touch, Chen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science, Technology Help Archaeologists Protect Relics (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To protect the timber, Chen's team has dug two pools to soak
the wood pieces in medicinal liquid.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time that protection of unearthed relics
goes parallel with the archaeological excavation," said Chen. The
budget for timber protection alone was 350,000 yuan (42,200 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the past, rare relics sometimes turned into ashes shortly
after they were dug out due to inefficient technological support.
Today, with the help of scientists, archaeologists can avoid
similar situations.
</P>
<P>
Wang Wuyu, site director with the Beijing Research Institute of
Cultural Heritage, said that DNA technology will be applied to
detect the age, gender and health condition of the occupant if
teeth or bones were discovered in the ancient tomb.
</P>
<P>
The excavation of the ancient tomb has been efficient and well
organized with scientists from different academic fields involved
in the project.
</P>
<P>
A plane carrying a high-resolution infrared detector has
conducted a remote examination over an area of three square
kilometers around Laoshan with the ancient tomb at the core.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time that China applied self-developed
remote technology to archaeological discovery," said Guo Huadong,
director of the institute of remote sensing of the Chinese Academy
of Sciences (CAS), China's top research institute of natural
sciences.
</P>
<P>
Experts who have worked on the pictures taken by the device
found four more sites that archaeologists might investigate. They
suggested that more ancient tombs may be at those sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
