<HEADLINE> Abu Sayyaf's Worry About Safety Defers Release of Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- No hostages have been released
Saturday by the Abu Sayyaf because the extremist Muslim group
alleged that there are military movements in their areas which
endanger their safety, government negotiators said.
</P>
<P>
Expectations ran high earlier in the day that the Abu Sayyaf
would free all the remaining hostages it held in Jolo island in
the southern province of Sulu. Captives of the group will be freed.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sayyaf rebels are still holding the remaining 13 hostages --
three Malaysians, two Germans, two Finns, two French, two South
Africans, one Lebanese and one Filipino they abducted from
Malaysia's resort island of Sipadan on April 23.
</P>
<P>
They also have in their hands three French TV journalist and 12
Filipino Christian evangelists who went to Jolo last month to
cover the hostage crisis and pray for the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Abu Sayyaf has released six Malaysians, one ailing
German woman and one Filipino of the Sipadan group, and one German
journalist and two local TV reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
