<HEADLINE> Russia Posts Second Win in Manila Leg of Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- World's No. 1 Russia showed poise
of a champion team Saturday, beating Italy 25-18, 20-25, 25-14, 25-
19 to clinch its second straight win in Manila leg of the 400,000-
U.S.-dollar 8th World Women's Volleyball Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
Still smarting from a near upset to the South Korean team
Friday, the Russians struggled hard in the first two sets before
unleashing their power in height advantage to dominate the third
and fourth sets en-route to their seventh overll win in eight
matches.
</P>
<P>
After the Italians took a 15-13 margin in the first set, the
Russians bounced back with a 12-3 windup spearheaded by multi-
awarded and veteran player Liouboy Chachkova Sokolova to claim the
opening set in 17 minutes.
</P>
<P>
However, the defending champion Russians failed to keep the
momentum as the Italians leaned on Darina Mifkova and Manuela
Leggeri to tie match at one all to the displeasure of Russian
veteran coach Nikolai Karpol, the national team mentor since 1988.
</P>
<P>
"I don't like our first two sets, my players didnot concentrate
as a team and they are not in focus of playing. Only one player
wants to play," said Karpol referring to Sokolova, the 1999 Grand
Prix best server.
</P>
<P>
Sokolova was also the Russians best scorer with 21 points in
their hard-earned 25-21 19-25, 18-25, 25-19, 15-13 victory on
Friday over the small but hard-fighting South Korean team.
</P>
<P>
Italian coach Angiglino Frigoni admitted that his players could
not contain the solid spike of the taller Russians who had 51 win
points on attack and block 19 attempts compared to Italy's 11
blocks.
</P>
<P>
The Russians played the Brazilians, who are also tote a 7-1 win-
lost card in Sunday for the Manila leg top prize of 40,000 dollars,
the same cash award which a top team in the China leg will receive.
Playing in China preliminary round include Cuba, United States,
Japan, and host China.
</P>
<P>
The four teams in China will arrive in Wednesday for the eight-
team
finals slated on August 24 to 27. The overall winner will receive
150,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The crowd-favorite Brazilians won their second straight match
following another sweeping of South Korean, 25-17, 25-22, 29-27,
in Saturday's second game. Brazil also swept Italy, 25-14, 25-20,
25-21 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rookie and newest-crowd favorite Erika Coimbra led Brazil anew
with 21 points in Saturday's match that saw darling of the crowd
Leila Barros scoring with only 3 points for Brazil, last year's
overall runner up to champion Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
