<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Aid Commitment to Nepal Rises in Fiscal 1999/2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Foreign aid commitment to
Nepal for the fiscal year 1999/2000 ending in mid-July increased
nominally to 19.79 billion rupees (282 million U.S. dollars),
according to the statistics by the Nepali Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Although the figure is 1.44 billion rupees (20 million dollars)
more than the previous year, the commitment is less than the
budget estimates for the year, which put the foreign aid
assistance at over 26 billion rupees (370 million dollars), said
the statistics available Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The aid commitment is mainly concentrated in areas such as
transportation, roads, primary education and hydropower, it said.
</P>
<P>
The statistics shows that Japan topped the bilateral donor list
with a total grant commitment of 4.9 billion rupees (70 million
dollars), followed by Norway, Germany, China and Finland, while
among the multilateral donors, the World Bank topped the
assistance list with a loan assistance of 4.06 billion rupees (58
million dollars), followed by the Asian Development Bank and the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
The committed aid, however, does not translate into
disbursement due to chronic problem in the absorptive capacity of
the national economy. Studies have shown that in some worst years
the disbursement is only about 33 percent of the commitment.
</P>
<P>
Nepal, one of the poorest countries in the world, heavily
depends on foreign aid for its development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
