<HEADLINE> Japanese Cities Protest Against U.S. Nuclear Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Nagasaki and Hiroshima, two
Japanese cities that experienced nuclear attacks, protested
Saturday against the United States' 12th subcritical nuclear test,
conducted Friday at an underground test site in Nevada, Kyodo News
reported.
</P>
<P>
"I am outraged at the testing and appeal to the international
community to start multilateral negotiations for an early
conclusion of a treaty banning all nuclear weapons," Nagasaki
Mayor Itcho Ito told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The city also sent a letter of protest to the U.S. Embassy in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Hiroshima city government also sent a letter of
protest to U.S. President Bill Clinton saying the United States
should immediately stop the tests as they dampen global efforts to
eliminate nuclear weapons, Kyodo quoted city officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The United States dropped atomic bombs on Nagasaki and
Hiroshima in 1945, killing more than 200,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
