<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Islam in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The introduction of Islam to
China saw frequent contacts between China and Arab countries. From
the Tang (618-907) to the Song (960-1279) dynasties, a continuous
stream of Muslim merchants from the Arab lands and Persia came to
China by sea and by Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
Many of the merchants married Chinese women and settled in
China and became the ancestors of today's Chinese Muslims. With
the conquest of Central and Western Asia by the Mongols in the
13th century, a large number of Arabs, Persians and Turks came and
settled down in China. Their common religious belief united them
into a new Muslim nationality -- the Chinese Hui.
</P>
<P>
These Hui Muslims have much in common with other Chinese
nationalities. Later, ethnic groups in northwestern China,
including the Uygur, Kazak, Ozbek, Tajik, Tatar, Kirgiz, Salar,
Dongxiang, and Bonan, converted to Islam.
</P>
<P>
The total population of the ten Muslim minorities in China now
stands at 20 million, mostly in Xinjiang, Ningxia, Gansu, and
Qinghai regions. They also scattered throughout China's vast
interior.
</P>
<P>
Life of the Muslims in China has improved by a big margin since
1949, when the People's Republic of China was established. Their
religious freedom is guaranteed by the Constitution and other laws.
</P>
<P>
In 1953, the China Islamic Association, a national organization
for China's Muslims, was set up. It plays an active role in
helping the government implement an all-round policy of freedom of
religion and popularizing Islamic culture. The Association
publishes a journal named Muslims in China and runs nine Islamic
theological institutes.
</P>
<P>
Today, there are 34,928 mosques, 45,051 Muslims teachers and
administrators, and 23,480 disciples studying in the Islamic
theological institutes in various regions.
</P>
<P>
Especially worth mentioning is that in the past, owning to
economic restrictions, only a few Chinese Muslims could afford to
pilgrimage to Mecca. Now, an unprecedented number of more than 5,
000 Chinese pilgrims visit Mecca every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Confirms Efforts for Release of Jailed Iranian Jews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government has
confirmed its involvement in international efforts to release 13
Jews detained in Iran on the charge of spying for Israel, the
Cyprus Mail newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
As three of the 13 Iranian Jews were acquitted in an Iranian
court ruling on July 1, the other 10 who were sentenced to two to
13 years in prison are due to appear in a court of appeal on
Saturday, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Some diplomatic sources attributed the hearing of the appeal by
the Iranian court to the international pressure. Cyprus, for about
a year, has joined the international efforts for the release of the
Jews.
</P>
<P>
"Cyprus and Iran enjoy very good relations and Cyprus respects
the principal of non-intervention in internal affairs of Iran and
the judiciary system. Any efforts we can make, to create a better
climate, we follow," Cyprus Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides
told the Cyprus Mail.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government noted that it did not exert any "pressure"
on Iran, and that any involvement was friendly and discreet.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian embassy in Nicosia was unavailable for comment so
far.   Iran has a Jewish community of about 25,000 people, the
largest
in the Middle East outside Israel. 
</P>
<P>
Since the arrest of the Jews early last year, Iran has been
under severe pressure from western countries to release them.
</P>
<P>
After the court verdict on July 1, western countries stepped up
their criticism and pressing Iran to overturn the sentences. Iran,
however, insists that the trial and verdict were rational and fair
and no foreign country should meddle in Iran's internal affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
