<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Tanzanian Presidential Candidates Join Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Four Tanzanian
presidential candidates entered the October 29 general elections
on Friday, the deadline set by the National Electoral Commission (
NEC) for returning presidential nomination forms.
</P>
<P>
The four contestants are current President Benjamin Mkapa of
the ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM), Augustine Mrema of the
Tanzanian Labor Party (TLP), Ibrahim Lipumba of Civic United
Front (CUF) and John Cheyo of the United Democratic Party (UDP).
</P>
<P>
They are the same contestants for the first multi-party
elections in 1995 when Mkapa won the presidency by collecting 61
percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
The NEC disqualified presidential candidates of the Tanzania
People's Party (TPP) and National Convention for Construction and
Reform (NCCR-Mageuzi) for failure to meet the legal requirements.
</P>
<P>
All the four presidential candidates and their running mates
for vice presidency returned the forms at the NEC head office amid
wild dance and songs by their supporters.
</P>
<P>
The NEC Chairman Justice Lewis Makame signed copies of the
forms, saying they would be displayed in a conspicuous place for
24 hours to allow for public scrutiny and objection if any.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that all the presidential candidates and
their running mates would be provided with security guard
throughout the campaign period.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has been under one party (CCM) system between 1965 and
1992 when the multi-party system was introduced.
</P>
<P>
The October 29 elections will be the second multi-party
elections since 1995, but the first time in the country's post-
independence history for presidential, parliamentary and civic
elections to be held simultaneously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Team Hopes to Rescue Russian Sub Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The commander of a British rescue
team said Friday that he hoped he might be able to save some of
the 118 sailors in the sunken Russian submarine Kursk by Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible if conditions are favorable and the Russians
give us permission to proceed that we could have rescued someone
by this time tomorrow," Commander Alan Hoskins told BBC at about
2200 GMT Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hoskins and his rescue crew are currently working around the
clock to get to the Russian submarine Kursk in the Barents Sea as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Commodore Tim Chittenden, who is head of the team's command
center in the Ministry of Defense base near Bath, a city in the
southwest of England, said that the team's spirits were very high
but the mood was very determined.
</P>
<P>
Hopes are increasingly pinned on the British rescue effort,
after an eighth Russian rescue mission failed to link with the
submarine Friday.
</P>
<P>
The rescue has become a race against time, as it is not known
how many of the 118 trapped sailors are still alive.
</P>
<P>
The Russian submarine has been stranded on the bed of the
Barents sea since last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A Norwegian boat carrying the British rescue team and mini-
submarine left Norway Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to arrive Saturday. "We just want to get them
there as fast as possible," said commodore Chittenden "I'm a
submariner, as are many involved in this operation, and we have no
other agenda than to get these guys out," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chittenden said his technical experts were working around the
clock to devise engineering solutions to the problems the team
faces.
</P>
<P>
He said they had received a huge amount of help from
specialists in private industry, including the oil and
construction sectors.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, a Russian rescue capsule reached an escape hatch on
the stricken nuclear submarine for the first time, but was unable
to latch on due to the heavy damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
