<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Taoism in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Taoism began in the 2nd century
AD. It is one of China's indigenous religions and derives its
ideology from ancient traditions including Huang-Lao, a learned
tradition named after Huang Di (the Yellow Emperor) and Lao-tzu
and followed by their devotees during the Western Han Dynasty (206
BC- 24 AD).
</P>
<P>
Because of the support from the emperors of the Tang (618-907)
and Song (960-1279) dynasties, Taoism entered a period of full
bloom and became an important religion in China, second only to
Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
Lao-tzu, who founded the early Qin Taoism school, is worshipped
as the forefather of Taoism, and the idea of the Way (Dao) that he
put forward in The Book of the Way of Power is the basis of the
religion.
</P>
<P>
Believing that Way is the origin of the universe and creates
all living beings, Taoists worship all life in the universe and
everything else created by nature. They also believe that man can
attain immortality and become a celestial being through practicing
austerities.
</P>
<P>
In the 12th century, Taoism gradually divided in two: Chuan-
chen Taoism and Cheng-i Taoism. The priests of Chuan-chen Taoism
renounced their families and lived together in temples. They were
vegetarian and practiced austerities in order to become immortal.
Many priests of Cheng-i Taoism, however, lived with their families
and did not avoid meat, and their ideas was to help others attain
good fortune and avoid the bad.
</P>
<P>
According to Taoism, the gods act as administrators and control
everything in the universe. Among the many gods worshipped by
Taoists, the God of the Primal Origin, the God of the Sacred Jewel,
and the God of the Way of Power (Lao-tzu) are regarded as the
supreme gods.
</P>
<P>
Many of the Taoist temples were built on mountains where,
according to tradition, celestial beings lived or ancient Taoists
had practiced austerities and become immortal. At present, there
are over 1,600 Taoist temples in China, home to more than 25,000
Taoist priests and nuns.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Taoist Association, established in 1957 in Beijing,
is a nationwide organization, with Min Zhiting as chairman. To
carry forward and spread the ancient Taoist culture, the
association has published dozens of Taoist classics and has
compiled more than 30 books about Taoism and a series of books on
Taoist culture. Apart from that, the association has a journal,
China Taoism, which is published every other month and distributed
both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Taoism, founded in 1990, offers
specialized classes for teaching students to become managerial
personnel of Taoist temples and advanced classes in the research
and teaching of Taoism. Hundreds of students have graduated from
the academy since its establishment.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Taoists have always maintained close contact with
Taoists all over the world. The Chinese Taoist Association is also
a member of the World Union of Religious and Environmental
Protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
