<HEADLINE> China's Demand for Cotton Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua)-- Confronted with a new surge in
cotton and textile exports, China is expected to cope with a rise
in domestic demand for cotton this year.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, China's textile firms had
seen exports rise by more than 40 percent and the country's cotton
exports rocketed by 121.9 percent to 212,200 tons in the first
half of this year from last year's.
</P>
<P>
Officials said any shortfall would be dealt with by channeling
part of the State's cotton reserves onto the market to avert any
sudden surge in cotton prices next year.
</P>
<P>
Fan Ning, an official with the State Textile Industry Bureau,
said he foresaw no major fluctuation in cotton prices in the
coming months, but prices this year would exceed last year's
record 2,000 yuan (241 U.S. dollars) per ton mark.
</P>
<P>
This resulted from the country's earlier decision to encourage
its largest cotton producer -- the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region -- to export more cotton, according to statistics from Fan'
s agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
