<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Top Legal News Events in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are top legal news
events in China last week:
</P>
<P>
Chinese Courts to Adopt Chief Justice System
</P>
<P>
China's Supreme People's Court has announced here that Chinese
courts at all levels will adopt the chief justice system to give a
bigger and, mostly, decisive say to chief justices.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference Wednesday, the supreme court issued the "
Methods on Selection of Chief Justice by People's Court (Trial)".
The document requires chief justices to be politically correct,
have a higher education, and be professionally experienced and
able.
</P>
<P>
China to Close Tax Loophole
</P>
<P>
Chinese lawmakers are due to review an amendment to the tax
collection law to prevent state taxes from being nibbled away.
</P>
<P>
The existing tax collection law cannot deal with the practice
of local authorities that mixed up local and central taxation and
diverted part of central revenues to local coffers, China Daily
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
 New Provision Issued for Lawyer Qualification Test
</P>
<P>
China has issued a new provision for Qualification Test of
Lawyer (QTL) this year, said an official from the Ministry of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
The revised provision amended measures about test application,
the assigning of test questions, test paper printing, test and
grading.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the new QTL provision stipulates 14 test subjects,
including constitution, nomology, system and practice of lawyer. A
committee to assign test questions will be set up and enrollment
will be limited within a certain quota.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
