<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Top Legal News Events in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Leaders in south China's Guangdong Provincial Justice
Department will have to be responsible for their subordinates who
break the law or violate disciplinary regulations, according to a
strict internal rule established recently.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen officials in the department have signed agreements in
this regard. Under the agreements, in a given year an official
will have no chance of promotion if any one of the subordinates is
found guilty of violating disciplinary regulations or the criminal
law; should there be two cases of violations, the official will
have to take the blame and be askd to resign.
</P>
<P>
12 Officials Punished for Reporting False Statistics
</P>
<P>
In Jiange, southwest China's Sichuan Province, 12 township
government officials were recently punished by local judicial
departments for reporting false statistics to higher authorities.
</P>
<P>
They were found to have submitted false statistical reports to
the higher level of government last year to show off their work
achievements.
</P>
<P>
 NPC Standing Committee to Open 17th Meeting
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress
(NPC), China's national legislature, will hold its 17th meeting in
Beijing from August 21 to 25.
</P>
<P>
There will be two draft laws for discussion at the meeting,
which are the National Current Language Law and the Extradition
Law. Draft amendments will also be made to the Patent Law, the
Fisheries Law and three other laws during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
China to Strengthen Ideological Education Among Judges
</P>
<P>
China's top judge Thursday called for strengthened ideological
and political education among judges of the country.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yang, president of the Supreme People's Court, made the
remark at a national conference on the ideology and publicity work
of the country's courts, which began Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
