<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Scientists Studying Anti-Hacking System
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have begun to research on an "anti-hacking
system" to prevent the rampage of hackers on the Internet,
according to the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
The study is being conducted by a group of experts led by Xu
Rongsheng, a research fellow with the High-Energy Physics
Institute under the CAS.
</P>
<P>
The scientists are working on basic theories, high technology
and effective ways to monitor and respond to the activities of
hackers, so as to ensure the safety of information networks.
</P>
<P>
Asia-Pacific Conference on Gifted Children Held in Beijing
</P>
<P>
The Sixth Asia-Pacific Conference on Giftedness with the theme
of "A New Millennium-A Gifted Future" is held in Beijing from
August 17 to 20.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is sponsored by China Science and Technology
Exchange Center and Institute of Psychology of Chinese Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are over 200 experts from the United
States, Germany, Australia, New Zealand, the Republic of Korea,
Thailand, Saudi Arabia and China.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft Sues Chinese Company for Piracy
</P>
<P>
Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's Court started the hearing of
Microsoft's anti-piracy case against ABD company on August 17.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft discovered last year that ABD's three computers
illegally installed Windows 95, Chinese Windows 98 and Chinese
Office 97.
</P>
<P>
ABD is a small computer manufacturer in the Zhongguancun
Technological Development Zone in Beijing. It was fined in
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft asked ABD for two million yuan in compensation and a
public apology. The main conflict between the two is the amount of
money.  
</P>
