<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Be Target in Anti-Poverty Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- China's poverty-alleviation
experts and gender advisers have asked for more attention be given
to poor women as part of a program to help people out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
A 20-year poverty-alleviation program is being drafted by the
State Council, Chen Fang, a research fellow with the Women's
Research Institute of the All-China Women's Federation, said.
</P>
<P>
"Gender awareness should be further incorporated into the
poverty-reduction program," Chen said. "Girls in poor areas still
do not have as many opportunities to go to school as boys, and
women still suffer most in poor areas."
</P>
<P>
Experts on women's issues believe women account for more than
60 percent of China's impoverished population. But most poverty-
alleviation projects in China do not give women special support.
</P>
<P>
Professor Du Xiaoshan, with the Poverty Research Center of the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, said income-generating
projects, education and medical services need assistance to lift
women from poverty.
</P>
<P>
Su Guoxia, division chief of the Policy Division of the State
Council's Poverty Alleviation Office, said advisers to the 20-year
project are considering literacy efforts, technical training and
health care to help women become better off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
