<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE -- Trade between the Czech Republic and the European
Union (EU) maintained a strong momentum of increase in the first
half of this year, the Czech newspaper "Hospodarske Noviny" (
Economic Daily) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Czech exports to the EU increased by 23.5 percent to 377.3
billion crowns (10 billion U.S. dollars) in the January-June
period of this year compared with the same period last year. And
its imports were worth 367.7 billion crowns (9.7 billion dollars),
an increase of 24.5 percent compared with the same period last
year, according to the latest statistics from the Czech
Statistical Office. (Czech-EU-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. trade deficit rose to a new record of 30.
6 billion U.S. dollars in June as U.S. imports of industrial
supplies and crude oil increased, the Commerce Department reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The June deficit was up 1 percent from May's 30.3 billion
dollars, which was revised down from the government's previous
estimate of 31 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Total imports of goods and services were up by 4.3 billion
dollars to 121.2 billion dollars in June. Exports increased by 4
billion dollars to 90.6 billion dollars. (US-Trade-Deficit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Euro zone's annual inflation rate in July remained
unchanged from the level in previous month at 2.4 percent, the
European Union's statistical office, Eurostat,said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The result, compared with 1.1 percent a year earlier, is yet
above the 2 percent limit set by the European Central Bank for a
stable economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the annual inflation rate for the 15-nation EU rose
to 2.2 percent in July from 2.1 percent in June. In July 1999, the
figure was 1.1 percent. (EU-Inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- U.S. monetary policymakers will vote to leave
interest rates unchanged at the next week's Federal Reserve Board
meeting, said a report released Friday by the investment
management group of Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
The bank's Capital Management expects no major surprises at the
Fed's meeting, although Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan "will likely warn that the Fed remains on guard against
inflation."
</P>
<P>
A final polling of economic reports leading up to the Fed's
meeting suggests that U.S. economic growth is moderating to a pace
that should be consistent with the Federal Reserve's platform, the
report said. (US-Interest) 
</P>
</TEXT>
