</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Prices Rising Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The fuel price increase by the
Chinese government this Thursday demonstrated its strong
commitment to bringing domestic oil product prices in line with
the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Planning Commission has increased the
retail price of 93-octane gasoline, the most used vehicle fuel in
China, to 3.2 yuan (0.39 U.S. dollars) from 3.07 yuan (0.37 U.S.
dollars) per litre. The price of diesel oil has also risen to 2.9
yuan from 2.76 yuan per litre.
</P>
<P>
Fuel dealers are permitted to raise or lower their prices by no
more than five percent from the benchmark levels, the commission
said.
</P>
<P>
The is the sixth price increase on oil products in the domestic
market since last November.
</P>
<P>
Li Shengsheng, deputy director of the Economic Research and
Consulting Center under the State Economic and Trade Commission,
attributed the consecutive price increases to high oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Domestic oil prices have surged in line with world oil price
hike this year. The central government has allowed domestic oil
prices to fluctuate according to world market changes since 1998.
</P>
<P>
World oil prices have stabilized at around 30 U.S. dollars per
barrel from less than ten U.S. dollars in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
"With the country's approaching entry into the World Trade
Organization (WTO), we must allow the domestic fuel prices to sway
in accordance with the world market variations," Li said.
</P>
<P>
China will cut its tariffs on fuel imports by a large margin to
about six percent, within the first one to two years after it
joins the WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000819.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Research Institutions Put on Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The state will require China's
270 government-subsidized research institutions to support
themselves in October this year.
</P>
<P>
It is a significant step towards reforming science and
technology administration, said Huang Qitao, a senior official
with the Ministry of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
The 270 institutions, previously attached to cabinet-level
administrations, could become technology firms or affiliate with
universities.
</P>
<P>
The Institute of Science and Technology Information of China, a
government-subsidized institution, has become a shareholding
company called Wanfang Data Co Ltd, pioneering this sort of change.
</P>
<P>
"Wanfang Data Co has set a good example for government-
subsidized institutions to free themselves from government
administrations," said Shang Yong, director of the ministry's
Department for Policy, Regulation and System Reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
