<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Leaves on Four-Nation South Asia Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro
Mori left here Saturday morning for Dhaka, the first stop of his
week-long tour of four South Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
The trip, which will take Mori to Bangladesh, Pakistan, India
and Nepal, is the first tour to South Asia by a Japanese prime
minister in a decade.
</P>
<P>
Mori is expected to arrive in Bangladesh on Saturday afternoon.
He is scheduled to make a two-day visit to Pakistan from Sunday
and leave for India on Monday, followed by a half-day visit to
Nepal on August 25.
</P>
<P>
During the trip, Mori plans to urge India and Pakistan to
resume their stalled peace talks and ease tension in the region,
Japanese government officials said.
</P>
<P>
Government sources said Mori will offer to resume some of
Japan's economic aid to India and Pakistan if leaders of the two
countries promise to continue a freeze on nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
In talks with leaders of the four countries, Mori is also
expected to exchange views on ways to expand bilateral ties and
economic cooperation, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Mori is slated to return to Japan August 26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
