<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Killed in Land Mine Explosions in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Six people were killed and one
injured in two mine explosions in the week in Bosnia, reports from
Sarajevo said.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian News Agency said that two mine clearance experts,
one Swedish and the other Bosnian, were killed Thursday in
Rogatica, 70 kilometers east of Sarajevo, when they stepped on
land mines while attempting to pull the bodies of two fishermen
who had been killed by mine explosions. A Serbian policeman was
also killed when he tried to rescue the two experts.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, a 17-year-old young man died and his brother
was wounded when they hit mines when collecting firewood in Bihac.
</P>
<P>
The mine clearance center in Bosnia appealed to local residents
again Friday to pay close attention to the danger of mines. It
said the Bosnian war ended, but the then battle fields were still
dangerous regions.
</P>
<P>
The center said that 347 people, 317 of them local residents
and 30 mine clearance experts, have been killed by mine explosions
in Bosnia since January 1996 after the peaceful agreement was
signed to end the war at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
There are 1,829 registered minefields throughout Bosnia, but
the center estimated that more than one million mines remain
strewn in around 30,000 minefields. About 1,500 persons are
engaged in mine clearance and they should spend about 10 years to
remove all of the mines, the center said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
