<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua, U.S. To Sign Anti-drug Maritime Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Nicaragua and the United States
will sign an anti-drug maritime agreement to intensify the war
against drug trafficking in the Central American country,
Nicaraguan Interior Minister Rene Herrera said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Herrera said, "We are consulting with the involved institutions.
The document, which is in the process of drafting, will be ready
for signing in two month."
</P>
<P>
The minister signed two memoranda with U.S. Ambassador Oliver
Garza on Friday, under which the United States pledges to grant
Nicaragua 800,000 U.S. dollars for combat against drug and
undocumented immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The two countries started negotiations two years ago on an anti-
drug maritime accord, which has met opposition from many political
group.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan Constitution forbids the establishment of
foreign military bases within national territory although it does
authorize the transit or stationing of foreign aircraft and
military equipment for humanitarian purposes.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica entered into a similar agreement with the United
States in 1998, which came into effect in November, 1999. The
armies of Honduras and the United States started joint maritime
patrolling in September of that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
