<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sotomayor, Freeman Hightlight Monaco Golden League Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Javier Sotomayor showed he is
still a major medal contender despite a year out of competition.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban high jumper had been cleared to compete in Sydney
when the world governing body halved his two-year drugs ban for
cocaine early this month.
</P>
<P>
The world record holder and 1992 Olympic champion cleared a
winning 2.30 metres at the Monaco golden league meeting on Friday,
his second competition since the suspension was lifted.
</P>
<P>
In the same day world champion Cathy Freeman, Australia's only
realistic hope of a track gold at the Sydney Olympics starting
next month, clocked 49.48 seconds, the fastest 400 metres time of
the year.
</P>
<P>
World champion and record holder Maurice Greene clocked 10.01
seconds in men's 100m race, repeating his victory in Zurich last
Friday in his second competition since pulling up lame in the U.S.
trials 200 metres final.
</P>
<P>
Gail Devers, twice the Olympic 100 champion and now chasing her
first Olympic 100 hurdles title, won again on Friday in 12.54
seconds
</P>
<P>
In women's 400m hurdles, Irina Privalova clocked 54.06 seconds
to score a morale-boosting win ahead of the American champion and
Olympic favourite Sandra Glover, who faded to the fourth in 54.51.
</P>
<P>
South African Llewellyn Herbert, the 1997 world silver medalist,
also upset an American, relegating Eric Thomas to third place in
the men's 400 hurdles.
</P>
<P>
Lydia Cheromei of Kenya fought a close battle with Tegla
Loroupe, Kenya's tiny world marathon record holder, before she
clocked 8:30.80 to take the women's 3,000 metres.
</P>
<P>
Algeria's world bronze medallist Djabir Said-Guerni won the men
's 800 metres ahead of Kenyan Commonwealth champion Japeth Kimutai
in 1:43.79, fourth fastest time in the world this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
