<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez Assumes Venezuelan Presidential Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Hugo Chavez assumed Saturday as
the first constitutional president of the Bolivarian Republic of
Venezuela for the 2000-2006 period.
</P>
<P>
Chavez was sworn in as president of Venezuela in a solemn
ceremony held at the new National Assembly (AN) building with his
right hand raised and the left on the new Bolivarian constitution,
and he received the presidential sash from AN Chairman William
Lara.
</P>
<P>
The event was witnessed by all the deputies, representatives of
all the public powers, governors, mayors and the diplomatic corps
accredited to Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bolivarian Constitution of Venezuela, the
president is committed to  have the constitution and the laws
fulfilled, to direct the government activities, to appoint and
remove the ministers, to direct the country's foreign affairs, and
is the commander in chief of the national armed forces.
</P>
<P>
It was the third time in two years Chavez has been sworn in,
as a result of the president's overhaul of political institutions
in this South American nation of 24 million people.
</P>
<P>
Calling Venezuela's current economic and social situation "
savage," Chavez promised Saturday to create a more equitable
society during his new term and to carry out an ambitious land
reform program. In international affairs, he urged "an end to the
bombardments, the embargoes, the sanctions and the threats of the
most powerful.''
</P>
<P>
"We will keep fighting for a multipolar world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chavez vowed to turn his attention to the ailing economy in his
new term. The economy has turned sour, shrinking by 7 percent last
year, during a boom in the international price of oil, Venezuela's
top export.
</P>
<P>
A Central Bank official said Friday that the economy was well
on its way to recovery, growing by about 2.5 percent in the year's
first half.
</P>
<P>
Chavez's leftist Patriotic Pole coalition won a big mandate in
July 30 elections. It gained three-fifths of a new, 165-member
unicameral legislature and 14 of 23 state governorships.
</P>
<P>
The new constitution gives Chavez a six-year term that can be
extended by another six years. The old 1961 constitution had five-
year terms and prohibited immediate re-election.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela has become, according to the new Venezuelan magna
charta of December 15, 1999, the first and only Latin American
country where the president can be at the helm of the country for
six years with a possibility of being immediately reelected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
