<HEADLINE> Some Southern African Countries to Export Maize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Some countries of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) will export maize in 2000/
2001 marketing year as the region projects a maize surplus of 1.34
million tons.
</P>
<P>
In its quarterly bulletin released here Sunday, the SADC
regional early warning unit said although cereal supplies have
remained insufficient with a deficit of 679,000 tons, some SADC
countries produced more than they needed.
</P>
<P>
The unit said the total maize availability projected at 21.05
million tons was sufficient to meet the region's maize requirement
of 19.71 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The unit said this would, however, boost export programs with
South Africa having so far made the commitment to export 565,000
tons of maize out of the country's availability of 2.27 million
tons for this crop.
</P>
<P>
Further exports are likely during the course of the 2000/2001
marketing year particularly to the drought-affected countries in
east Africa, said the unit.
</P>
<P>
Exportable maize surpluses were also projected for Malawi,
Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the SADC early warning unit said wheat availability
estimated at 3.29 million tons was insufficient to cover regional
requirement of 4.5 million tons leaving a regional deficit of 1.21
million tons.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the region would also export rice, sorghum and
millet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
