<HEADLINE> S.Africa Calls for Speedy Implementation of Congo Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Signatories to the Lusaka
peace agreement should not let themselves be held to ransom by
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) President Laurent Kabila,
South African Foreign Affairs Minister Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma said
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the South African Broadcasting Corporation
television program, she said regional leaders will decide whether
to institute punitive measures against the DRC as soon as they
hear Kabila's response to the latest peace initiative.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether sanctions will work in getting Kabila to the
negotiating table, Dlaminis-Zuma replied: "They probably would
work to some degree."
</P>
<P>
The prospect of sanctions was raised during a gathering of
African leaders in Lusaka this week where participants failed to
persuade Kabila to accept the mediation of former Botswana
president Ketumile Masire.
</P>
<P>
Kabila has accused Masire, who was appointed by the
Organization of African Unity, of bias toward the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese leader was told in the latest Lusaka meeting "in
a very firm way" to reconsider his stance.
</P>
<P>
Dlamini-Zuma said implementation of the year-old Lusaka accord
should start and be accelerated by the five governments who had
signed it along with the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"They should not be held at ransom by one person," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan said on Friday that he was
sending Nigeria's former military ruler General Abdulsalami
Abubakar to tell the Congolese government to honor the accord.
</P>
</TEXT>
