<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Ruling Party Promises to Improve Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's ruling Chama
Cha Mapinduzi (CCM) has put modernization of the economy and
empowerment of the people as its key targets in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
The party's 2000 elections manifesto, which was officially
launched by its chairman, the incumbent president Benjamin Mkapa
on Saturday and made available here on Sunday, states that the
commendable social and economic progress was achieved in Tanzania
over the last couple of years, but the economy had remained
backward and dependent.
</P>
<P>
"The challenge ahead of us is to expand the economy and lead
Tanzanians out of traditional agriculture, livestock keeping and
fishing, as well as serfdom in the emerging market economy," the
124-page manifesto says.
</P>
<P>
"It is from such a background that CCM has now conceived a
strategy aimed at economically empowering the people."
</P>
<P>
The strategy, it notes, involves the creation of an environment
conductive to popular participation in economic activities and
poverty reduction programs.
</P>
<P>
It also includes strengthening of the cooperative movement in
the country to facilitate availability of inputs to farmers at
affordable prices and markets for their produce.
</P>
<P>
"In the next five years," the party declared in the manifesto,
"modern and scientific and technological processes are to be
applied in all sectors of the economy."
</P>
<P>
The party also pledges to continue with policies designed to
attract more investment in the mining, manufacturing, tourism and
other economic sectors to boost the country's economic growth to
over 4 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania will hold its second multi-party presidential and
parliamentary elections on October 29. Mkapa is running for a
second five-year term as a CCM candidate, while the party is
trying to gain more seats in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
In the last elections in 1995, the CCM achieved a convincing
majority at the national legislative elections, winning 186 of the
232 elective seats in the National Assembly, the parliament of
Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
