<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian authorities have
arrested four foreigners including two Britons, a South African
and a Sierra Leonean on spying charges, according to a radio
report on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Liberian Justice Minister Eddington Varmah was quoted by the
British Broadcast Corporation as saying at a news conference held
Saturday that the four, who are in Liberia to make a documentary
for Britain's Channel Four television, have carried out "acts
against the security of the state".
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the police discovered this group
damaging instruments against the interests of the Liberian country
in an attempt to provide false and malicious information to
foreign powers.
</P>
<P>
They were arrested in their hotel rooms in Liberia's capital
Monrovia on Friday and will appear before a court in the near
future, Varmah said.
</P>
<P>
The British Television employing them has denied the spying
allegations, saying that it is "deeply concerned" and that the
crew was engaged in legitimate journalistic activities.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, Liberia has repeatedly denounced what it says
are international plots against its President Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
Ties between Britain and Liberia have been on the strain since
Britain recommended the European Union to cancel an aid package to
Liberia for its alleged supporting the rebels in Sierra Leone.
</P>
