<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Opposition Presidential Candidate Vows to Rid Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A major Tanzanian
opposition presidential candidate has promised to uproot
corruption and develop the country's economy through proper
utilization of the natural resources available if he wins the
election scheduled on October 29, newspapers here reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Launching the election campaigns here on Saturday, Ibrahim
Lipumba, a candidate who is running for the highest position in
the Tanzanian Union government on the ticket of the alliance of
the Civic United Front (CUF) and the CHADEMA, said that their
parties will wage an endless war against corruption and ensure
Tanzanians may live in a corruption-free country.
</P>
<P>
Lipumba, a professor of economics, said: "Much efforts will be
directed to the improvement of the economy by investing much in
agriculture and industries because they, important sectors, in
developing the nation."
</P>
<P>
This can be done through the provision of agricultural inputs
and soft loans to the peasants all over the country, he told the
rally.
</P>
<P>
"With the rehabilitation of our collapsing industries," he
added: "We would be able to create more jobs for our youth who are
roaming the streets on empty stomachs."
</P>
<P>
Lipumba, who comes from the biggest opposition party of CUF, is
one of the four union presidential candidates who returned their
presidential nomination forms on Friday, the deadline set by the
National Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
The other contestants are the incumbent President Benjamin
Mkapa of the ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM), Augustine Mrema of
the Tanzanian Labor Party (TLP) and John Cheyo of the United
Democratic Party (UDP).
</P>
<P>
They are the same contestants for the 1995 elections, the first
under the multiparty system in which Mkapa won by collecting 62
percent of the votes and Lipumba won 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania had been under a single political party (CCM) system
from 1965 until 1992 when the multiparty system was introduced.
</P>
