<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Commercial Bank (KCB),
one of the country's five major financial institutions, is to
spend some 1.2 billion shillings (about 16 million U.S. dollars)
in its retrenchment program to reduce its work force to 3,500 by
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Standard newspaper quoted KCB chief executive Gareth
George as saying as a measure to reduce operational expenses, the
bank will lay off over 500 employees.
</P>
<P>
"Many in senior positions have opted for early retirement and
the retrenchment of staff is on a voluntary basis," said George,
when he was addressing the business community from North Rift
region at Eldoret town in western Kenya.
</P>
<P>
George said his bank's total lending stands 45 billion
shillings (about 600 million dollars), of which a third is non-
performing loans, adding that his bank has reduced its base rate
to 16 percent, the lowest in the market.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive also admitted that for the last two years,
the service delivery of the bank has not been good.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that several new appointments will be made,
including that of IT director and finance director, to assist him
in bringing KCB back to a profit-making institution. 
</P>
