<HEADLINE> Toxic Chemicals at Zambian Mine Stolen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Part of Forty-four drums
containing close to 10,000 liters of toxic substances stuck at
Kitwe's Nkana mine, Copperbelt Province in Zambia, are believed to
have been stolen, thereby raising fears that hundreds of
unsuspecting miners have been exposed to the fatal chemicals,
Sunday Times of Zambia newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, a reasonable quantity of the poisonous
material called Polychlorinated Biphenyls (PCBs) is suspected to
have been stolen by some Kitwe residents after vandals broke into
the waste storehouse and stole two drums and sold the contents as
ordinary cooking oil.
</P>
<P>
The PCB oil which is harmful to both human beings and the
environment has been in the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM)
designated storehouse for the past 15 years after being drained
out of equipment at the site.
</P>
<P>
Cyril Lukeke, a ZCCM Investment Holding official, told a group
of participants of a national PCB conference in Kitwe this week,
that ZCCM needed about 700,000 U.S. dollars to dispose off all
toxic and hazardous waste.
</P>
<P>
He explained during a tour of the PCB site that ZCCM Investment
Holdings also needed to buy United Nations-approved containers to
transfer the chemicals from the site to the final destination to
avoid any spillages.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a drop of PCB on a human skin causes
rashes, cancer and accelerates puberty and contaminates the soil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
