<HEADLINE> Former Zambian Minister Launches New Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Former Zambian Environment
Minister Ben Mwila has officially launched his Republican Party (
RP) with an immediate call to fight corruption and politics of
intolerance, Sunday Times of Zambia newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Luanshya's Rugby Club in Copperbelt Province on
Saturday, Mwila, also chairman of the RP, said his party would
ensure that the Anti-Corruption Commission (ACC) was funded,
allowed to run independently and empowered to root out corrupt
leaders and citizens in the country.
</P>
<P>
On the performance of the economy, he said his party would
ensure that the economy was turned around with the help of all
stakeholders especially the farming community.
</P>
<P>
The party would resuscitate the agricultural sector, using a
combination of incentives such as affordable credit, speedy
collection and timely payment for agricultural produce.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Mwila as saying that his party once elected
into office would ensure that all citizens had access to basic
health facilities and care through the establishment of combined
private and public health schemes such as medical and insurance
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Mwila lost his minister portfolio after he was expelled for the
country's ruling party, Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD),
last month. He was suspended in June this year by MMD National
Secretary Michael Sata, who charged that in the past 18 months,
Mwila had been involved in anti-party activities which greatly
destabilized the party.
</P>
<P>
Mwila announced his candidature for the MMD presidency on May
26 this year in a bid to run for the MMD presidency in the general
elections to be held next year. 
