<HEADLINE> Uganda to Disseminate Storage Technics to Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan Ministry of
Agriculture has started a program to disseminate post harvest
storage technologies to farmers, with the aim to educate farmers
on simple local developed technologies to preserve food, the
government-owned New Vision daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Over 35 percent of the total produce is wasted because our
farmers do not have simple technologies to store their produce,"
Head of National Post-harvest Program Ambrose Agona was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Our experience has found that a few months after the harvest
season, communities fall back to famine because we lack post-
harvest produce handling techniques," said Agona.
</P>
<P>
He said that insects, micro-organisms, rodents, mites and birds
pose the biggest threat to post harvesting storage.
</P>
<P>
The program has developed simple preservation methods through
the use of tobacco and a kind of tree powder, said Agona, adding
that when mixed in cereal produce, the powder has a strong smell
which repulses weevils for over six months.
</P>
<P>
Post-harvest storage methods are of importance to Ugandans, for
the east Africa country is an agricultural country with over 80
percent of population being farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
