<HEADLINE> Three People Injured in Belfast Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Two men and one woman were
injured in a shooting in a Protestant stronghold of Belfast on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The BBC said gunmen opened fire in a clash between supporters
of rival pro-British Ulster Volunteer Force (UVF) and the fringe
Loyalist Volunteer Force guerrillas during a loyalist parade in
the Shankill area of the Northern Irish capital.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of loyalists, some wearing paramilitary-style
uniforms, took part in the parade along the Shankill Road to mark
the completion of murals daubed on walls in the area depicting
their pro-British culture.
</P>
<P>
Among the paraders were former Ulster Freedom Fighters
commander Johnny Adair, who was released from prison last year
under the 1998 Good Friday Agreement after serving four years of a
16-year sentence for directing loyalist paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
The shooting was expected to raise tensions in the Shankill
Road area, which has seen a number of Protestant and Catholic
houses damaged over the past 10 days in a series of attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
