<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Of Germans Rally Against Right-extremism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Berlin, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Several thousand people took to
the streets on Saturday to condemn right extremism in Germany,
while Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder renewed call for banning the
ultra rightist National-democratic Party of Deutschland (NPD).
</P>
<P>
In the city of Hamburg, about 2,500 people participated in a
protest with the theme of "Hamburg Against Nazi-Terror," which
display their anger at the growing violence of right-extremists
against foreigners and Jews. Dorothee Stapelfeldt, president of
the Hamburg state house, urged citizens to make more efforts for a
"democratic Hamburg" by standing up against the right-extremist
skinheads.
</P>
<P>
In estern German cities of Rostock and Eisenach, there were
also anti-right-extremism demonstrations sponsored by an alliance
of organizations named "Action Day Against Rightism".
</P>
<P>
As reported by "Bild am Sonntag," German Chancellor Schroeder
called on Bundestag and Bundesrat, the two chambers of the federal
parliament, to send a joint resolution on banning the NPD to the
Constitutional Court, if a working group of federal and state
officials recommends such a move.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said he believed such a move would be a piece of "
political hygiene," and that a joint resolution would increase
pressure on the conservative high court.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, "Tageszeitung", a Berlin-based newspaper, published
on its front pictures of 22 ultra-right wingers in Germany, at the
start of its campaign against extremism. The Norddeutsche Rundfunk
(NDR), a broadcasting service, also carried out its "Against
Hatred--For Tolerance" initiative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
